# Pre-requisites {#pre-requisites}

This document assumes that you already have:

* A Deployed Openshift Cluster (May be SNO, Compact Cluster or full deployment)  
* Configured Storage on this Cluster and have a default StorageClass  
* Appropriate DNS entries for the spoke cluster being deployed with CAPI

When deploying a spoke cluster from a hub cluster using CAPI and Metal3, the general deployment process goes like this:

* Register BareMetal Hosts with Metal3  
* Metal3 creates a Configuration Drive image with Ignition and **deployed** network configuration  
* Metal3 starts nodes using a base image & **provisioning** network configuration  
* Metal3 writes RHCOS image and Configuration Drive image to disk & reboots node  
* At this point, Metal3 considers the node to be deployed  
* Node boots RHCOS and uses ignition to install OpenShift Container Platform

Please note that there are TWO different networking configurations you will be creating during this process. One for the BareMetal Host to boot and connect to the provisioning network.  The second is for the BareMetal Host to boot to the OpenShift Machine Network.  These may be the same network but they do not have to be. For our documentation purposes here and the POC, they are the same network.

# Prepare Hub Cluster for CAPI Use {#prepare-hub-cluster-for-capi-use}

Deployment of spoke clusters using CAPI requires Multicluster Engine on a hub cluster and enabling preview features within the Operator.

## Install Multicluster Engine (MCE) Operator {#install-multicluster-engine-(mce)-operator}

Navigate to **Operators**\-\>**Operator Hub**  
Search by keyword: **multicluster**  
![][image1]

Click on **multicluster engine for Kubernetes**, click **Install**.  
Accept Defaults.

When the installation completes, click **Create MultiCluster Engine**.  
Accept Defaults.

From the CLI you can monitor this by watching the resource:

```shell
watch oc get mce
```

Wait for the status to become **Available**.

If you are using a SNO environment, you will need to create the **Provisioning** Resource as it is not deployed by default.  If you are unsure, you can check if you have the resource:

```shell
$ oc get provisioning
NAME                         AGE
provisioning-configuration   5h38m
```

If this does not return anything, you will need to create the resource. Do so as such:

```shell
cat > provisioning.yaml << EOF
apiVersion: metal3.io/v1alpha1
kind: Provisioning
metadata:
  name: provisioning-configuration
spec:
  provisioningNetwork: Disabled
  watchAllNamespaces: true
EOF
oc apply -f provisioning.yaml
```

If you just created the **Provisioning** resource with the above YAML, you do not have to patch it to watch all namespaces.  If the **Provisioning** resource already existed, patch it to watch all namespaces:

```shell
oc patch provisioning provisioning-configuration \
   --type merge -p '{"spec":{"watchAllNamespaces": true }}'
```

## Edit MCE to Enable CAPI {#edit-mce-to-enable-capi}

Edit MCE and enable three settings to enable CAPI use:

```shell
oc edit multiclusterengines.multicluster.openshift.io -n multicluster-engine
```

Search for the word ***preview*** to find the stanzas we are looking for.  We need to enable the following 3 settings:

* cluster-api  
* cluster-api-provider-metal3-preview  
* cluster-api-provider-openshift-assisted-preview

Note the formatting because it might be a bit confusing.  Each stanza starts with **configOverrides** and ends with the **name** of the setting with **enabled** ABOVE the setting name:

![][image2]

Enable those 3 settings by changing **false** to **true** and save the file:

![][image3]

After you make these changes, you can see the services starting in the multicluster-engine namespace:

```shell
oc get mce  # You will see the MCE begin to update
oc get pods -n multicluster-engine | egrep '(capoa|capm3|capi)' # as pods start
```

## Enable Central Infrastructure Management {#enable-central-infrastructure-management}

The Central Infrastructure Management is the back end store for all of the data to manage the deployment of your spoke environments.  You should carefully consider the sizing strategy you use here because once you create this, you can’t resize this (as far as I know).

You can enable CIM by applying the following:

```shell
apiVersion: agent-install.openshift.io/v1beta1
kind: AgentServiceConfig
metadata:
  name: agent
spec:
  databaseStorage:
    accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
    resources:
      requests:
        storage: 10Gi     # See details below regarding sizing
  filesystemStorage:
    accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
    resources:
      requests:
        storage: 100Gi    # See details below regarding sizing
  imageStorage:
    accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
    resources:
      requests:
        storage: 50Gi    # See details below regarding sizing
```

**databaseStorage**: This value specifies how much storage is allocated for storing files such as database tables and database views for the clusters. The minimum value that is required is 1Gi. You might need to use a higher value if there are many clusters.

**filesystemStorage**: This value specifies how much storage is allocated for storing logs, manifests, and kubeconfig files for the clusters.  The minimum value that is required is 1Gi, but the recommended value is at least 100Gi. Expectation is each cluster to consume 200M and 2-3Gi for each supported Openshift Container Platform Version. You might need to use a higher value if there are many clusters.

**imageStorage**: This value specifies how much storage is allocated to store base Red Hat Enterprise Linux CoreOS images. The minimum value is 10Gi, but the value for best practice is at least 50Gi, especially if you are opting for the default set of images instead of defining a limited set. You need to allow at least 2Gi of image storage for each instance of Red Hat Enterprise Linux CoreOS.

Your central infrastructure management service is configured. You can verify that it is healthy by checking the **assisted-service** and **assisted-image-service** deployments and ensuring that their pods are ready and running.

```shell
oc get pods -n multicluster-engine | grep assisted
```

# Deploying a Cluster using CAPI {#deploying-a-cluster-using-capi}

## Common Resources (Regardless of Deployment Type) {#common-resources-(regardless-of-deployment-type)}

When deploying a cluster with CAPI, there are a number of different objects created within OpenShift Kubernetes.  OpenShift can be deployed in three different architecture topologies:

* Single Node OpenShift (SNO) \- This is a single node that acts as both a controller & worker  
* Compact Cluster \- This is a 3 node cluster where all three nodes act as both a controller & worker  
* Full Deployment \- This is a 4 (or more) node cluster where there are 3 controller nodes & 1 or more worker nodes.  For “Full Deployments” of 5 or less total nodes, the controllers are deployed as worker nodes too by default. You can change this post deployment.  For deployments of 6 or greater nodes, 3 nodes are dedicated controller nodes by default.

The Single Node Openshift and the Compact Cluster have basically the same set of Resources that are created with the only difference being the replica count and possibly the label selector for the nodes.  The Full Deployment uses the same set of resources and has additional resources for configuring the Worker Nodes. This document will cover the required resources for each topology type.

### Create a Project (Namespace) for Your Cluster Objects {#create-a-project-(namespace)-for-your-cluster-objects}

You will want to keep all of the object for a cluster in a single namespace which makes it easy to clean up everything you create by simply deleting the namespace.

```shell
oc new-project cluster-t1
```

Once you create this, it will then be your active namespace for any objects/commands you create/use when you do not specify the namespace.

### Add Baremetal Hosts to Metal3 {#add-baremetal-hosts-to-metal3}

Each Baremetal Host is going to need:

* 2 Secrets \- One for the BMC credentials; One for the provisioning network NMState configuration  
* 1 Baremetal Host Definition

Here is how each object relates to each other:

![][image4]

You will note that in these examples, I am providing two labels for each of these BareMetalHost resources: **node** and **role**.  In the SNO deployment, we will use the **node** label to specify which node we are deploying SNO to while for a compact cluster or full deployment, we will use the **role** label.  Adding the two labels to the resources now allows us to use the resources appropriately for any topology. Do not use dashes in the label definitions or values.

```shell
cat > dell-r660-1.yaml << EOF 
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret    # Secret for BMC Credentials
metadata:
  labels:
    environment.metal3.io: baremetal
  name: dell-r660-1-idrac-creds
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
data:
  password: AAAAAAA    # Set this to the base64 encoded value of the password
  username: BBBBBBBB  # Set this to the base64 encoded value of the user
type: Opaque
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret  # Secret fo NMState Provisioning
metadata:
  name: dell-r660-1-network
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
data:
  nmstate: ZG5zLXJlc……      # Set this to the base64 encoded nmstate file
type: Opaque
---
apiVersion: metal3.io/v1alpha1
kind: BareMetalHost
metadata:
  name: dell-r660-1
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
  labels:
    role: controller
    node: dellr6601
  annotations:
    inspect.metal3.io: disabled
spec:
  automatedCleaningMode: metadata
  bmc:
    address: 'redfish-virtualmedia://192.168.0.10/redfish/v1/Systems/System.Embedded.1'
    credentialsName: dell-r660-1-idrac-creds #  Match Secret Name Above
    disableCertificateVerification: true
  bootMACAddress: '6C:92:CF:AA:AA:AA'
  online: false
  preprovisioningNetworkDataName: dell-r660-1-network #  Match Secret Name Above
  rootDeviceHints:
    deviceName: /dev/nvme0n1
EOF
```

Things to Update:

First Secret \- BMC Credentials

* Update the **username** for the BMC  
* Update the **password** for the BMC  
* Update the **name** of the object to something meaningful for you

Second Secret \- NMState Configuration file

* Update the **name** of the object to something meaningful for you  
* Update the **nmstate** value to a base64 encoded version of the NMState file. See example below.

BareMetalHost 

* Update the **name** of the object to something meaningful for you  
* Update the **labels** for this node, these will be used in selecting nodes for provisioning; Two recommended labels are **node** and **role**.  Do not use dashes in your label definitions.  
* Note the annotation **inspect.metal3.io: disabled** which will disable node inspection. Node inspection is a process where Metal3 boots the node and gathers hardware information on the node.  It is not necessary for what we are doing here so we disable it. Remove the annotation if you want the node to inspect.  
* Update the **BMC Address** to the Redfish URL for your server  
* Update **credentialsName** to the name of the **first secret**  
* Update the **bootMACAddress** to a MAC on the server; This is needed when PXE booting, but since we are using Redfish/Virtual Media, this is not used, however Metal3 enforces all BMH to have a unique value here, so it’s best to set it to the first NIC MAC on the server  
* Update the **preprovisioningNetworkDataName** to the name of the **second secret**  
* Update **deviceName** to specify the drive to install the operating system on.  If you do not want to specify this, you can remove the whole **rootDeviceHints** section and the installer will try to do its best to select the optimal disk.  *See additional note below on this.*  
   

In the above file, you will need to base64 encode a number of values. The shorter ones, such as the **username** and **password** can easily be done by echoing them to base64:

```shell
$ echo root | base64
cm9vdAo=
```

But for large values, such as an **NMStateConfig** file, you need to provide the **\-w0** switch to base64 to disable wrapping so the output is a single line versus multi-line content.

Here is a sample NMState Configuration file:

```shell
cat > dell-r660-1-bmh-nmstate-decoded.yaml << EOFdns-resolver:
  config:
    server:
    - 172.16.0.5
interfaces:
- ipv4:
    dhcp: false
    enabled: false
  ipv6:
    enabled: false
  link-aggregation:
    mode: 802.3ad
    options:
      downdelay: 200
      lacp_rate: 1
      miimon: 100
      updelay: 200
      xmit_hash_policy: layer2+3
    port:
    - eno12399np0
    - eno12409np1
  mtu: 9000
  name: bond0
  state: up
  type: bond
- name: bond0.2100
  type: vlan
  state: up
  vlan:
    base-iface: bond0
    id: 2100
  ipv4:
    address:
    - ip: 172.17.0.12
      prefix-length: 24
    dhcp: false
    enabled: true
  mtu: 9000
routes:
  config:
  - destination: 0.0.0.0/0
    next-hop-address: 172.17.0.1
    next-hop-interface: bond0.2100
    table-id: 254
EOF
```

And here is the base64 version:

```shell
cat dell-r660-1-bmh-nmstate-decoded.yaml | base64 -w0

```

***Note on rootDiskHints***: One needs to consider the disks that are being installed on in relation to the RHCOS image that will be installed.  Some newer disks have 4k block sizes as their default versus 512 and therefore require a 4k disk image to install on to them (see [issue](https://issues.redhat.com/browse/COS-834)) so you may want to force the RHCOS image onto a non 4k disk if you are not using a 4k image.

Once configured, apply your BMH files to create your baremetal hosts.

```shell
oc apply -f dell-r660-1.yaml
```

You can monitor your BareMetal Hosts:

```shell
watch oc get bmh
```

The BareMetal Host will first go into **Registering** status and then they will either go to **Available** or start Inspection if you removed the annotation for disabling inspection.  Ultimately, you want the node to become **Available**.

### Configure NMStateConfig for the OpenShift Deployed Network Configuration {#configure-nmstateconfig-for-the-openshift-deployed-network-configuration}

Each node that will be deployed needs a **NMStateConfig** file that defines the networking configuration of the **deployed** node.  In a previous step, we created a base64 encoded NMState Configuration for the BareMetal Host that is used when the node boots for **inspection** or **provisioning**.  This **NMStateConfig** is configured on the host POST provisioning and represents what the OpenShift Cluster Node Network should be configured as.

You will note that in these examples, I am providing two labels for each of these NMStateConfig files: **node** and **role**.  In the SNO deployment, we will use the **node** label to specify which node we are deploying SNO to while for a compact cluster or full deployment, we will use the **role** label.  Adding the two labels to the resources now allows us to use the resources appropriately for any topology.  Do not use dashes in the label definitions or values.

```shell
cat > dell-r660-1-ocp-nmstate.yaml << EOF
apiVersion: agent-install.openshift.io/v1beta1
kind: NMStateConfig
metadata:
  labels:
    # Must match what is in nmStateConfigLabelSelector
    # in OpenshiftAssistedControlPlane and CAN NOT CONTAIN DASHES
    node: dellr6601
    role: controller
  name: dell-r660-1
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
spec:
  config:
    dns-resolver:
      config:
        server:
        - 172.16.0.5
        - 172.16.0.6
    interfaces:
    - ipv4:
        dhcp: false
        enabled: false
      ipv6:
        enabled: false
      link-aggregation:
        mode: 802.3ad
        options:
          downdelay: 200
          lacp_rate: 1
          miimon: 100
          updelay: 200
          xmit_hash_policy: layer2+3
        port:
        - eno12399np0
        - eno12409np1
      mtu: 9000
      name: bond0
      state: up
      type: bond
    - name: bond0.2100
      type: vlan
      state: up
      vlan:
        base-iface: bond0
        id: 2100
      ipv4:
        address:
        - ip: 172.17.0.12
          prefix-length: 24
        dhcp: false
        enabled: true
      mtu: 9000
    - ipv4:
        dhcp: false
        enabled: false
      ipv6:
        enabled: false
      link-aggregation:
        mode: 802.3ad
        options:
          downdelay: 200
          lacp_rate: 1
          miimon: 100
          updelay: 200
          xmit_hash_policy: layer2+3
        port:
        - eno12419np2
        - eno12429np3
      mtu: 9000
      name: bond1
      state: up
      type: bond
    - ipv4:
        dhcp: false
        enabled: false
      ipv6:
        enabled: false
      link-aggregation:
        mode: 802.3ad
        options:
          downdelay: 200
          lacp_rate: 1
          miimon: 100
          updelay: 200
          xmit_hash_policy: layer2+3
        port:
        - ens2f0np0
        - ens2f1np1
      mtu: 9000
      name: bond2
      state: up
      type: bond
    routes:
      config:
      - destination: 0.0.0.0/0
        next-hop-address: 172.17.0.1
        next-hop-interface: bond0.2100
        table-id: 254
  interfaces:
  - macAddress: 6C:92:CF:AA:AA:AA
    name: eno12399np0
  - macAddress: 6C:92:CF:AA:AA:AB
    name: eno12409np1
  - macAddress: 6C:92:CF:BB:BB:BB
    name: eno12419np2
  - macAddress: 6C:92:CF:BB:BB:BC
    name: eno12429np3
  - macAddress: B4:83:51:CC:CC:CC
    name: ens2f0np0
  - macAddress: B4:83:51:CC:CC:CD
    name: ens2f1np1
EOF
oc apply -f dell-r660-1-ocp-nmstate.yaml
```

Create a NMStateConfig for each node of your deployed cluster and apply it.

The last common resource is the [Cluster](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api/cluster.x-k8s.io/Cluster/v1beta1@v1.0.0)  itself. This YAML defines the internal networking of the OpenShift Cluster, similar to the **install-config.yaml**.  Additionally, it makes references to the **OpenshiftAssistedControlPlane** Object and the **Metal3Cluster** Objects which are defined when we get down to the topology sections:

```shell
cat > resourceCluster.yaml <<EOF
apiVersion: cluster.x-k8s.io/v1beta1
kind: Cluster
metadata:
  name: cluster-t1
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
spec:
  clusterNetwork:
    pods:
      cidrBlocks:
        - 172.18.0.0/20
    services:
      cidrBlocks:
        - 10.96.0.0/12
  controlPlaneRef: 
    apiVersion: controlplane.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1alpha2
    kind: OpenshiftAssistedControlPlane
    name:  cluster-t1-oacp
    namespace: project-cluster-t1
  infrastructureRef: 
    apiVersion: infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1beta1
    kind: Metal3Cluster
    name: cluster-t1-m3cluster
    namespace: project-cluster-t1
EOF
oc apply -f resourceCluster.yaml
```

Regardless of the Deployment Type you are performing, you can create all of the resources in any order with the exception of the [**Metal3MachineTemplates**](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/metal3-io/cluster-api-provider-metal3/infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/Metal3MachineTemplate/v1beta1@v1.10.1).  Create those last as once you create those, provided all of the other resources exist, the deployment should commence.

## Deployment Type: Single Node Openshift {#deployment-type:-single-node-openshift}

### Single Node Openshift Resource Map {#single-node-openshift-resource-map}

Here is a Topology Map of the necessary resources for deploying a Single node Openshift (SNO) cluster. The arrows show references, so for example, in the [Cluster](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api/cluster.x-k8s.io/Cluster/v1beta1@v1.0.0) resource definition, you will see references to both the OpenshiftAssistedControlPlane resource and the [Metal3Cluster](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/metal3-io/cluster-api-provider-metal3/infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/Metal3Cluster/v1beta1@v1.10.1) resource.

![][image5]

Notice that every resource above stems out from the [Cluster](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api/cluster.x-k8s.io/Cluster/v1beta1@v1.0.0) resource we created in the previous section when we created all of the Common Resources. Let’s go ahead and create the  [Metal3Cluster](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/metal3-io/cluster-api-provider-metal3/infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/Metal3Cluster/v1beta1@v1.10.1) that is referenced by the [Cluster](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api/cluster.x-k8s.io/Cluster/v1beta1@v1.0.0) Object.  [**Metal3Cluster**](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/metal3-io/cluster-api-provider-metal3/infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/Metal3Cluster/v1beta1@v1.10.1) is the Schema for the [**Metal3Cluster**](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/metal3-io/cluster-api-provider-metal3/infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/Metal3Cluster/v1beta1@v1.10.1) API and it defines the desired state of the cluster. The endpoint defined here will be your **\<cluster-name\>.\<base domain\>** of your deployed spoke OpenShift Cluster.

```shell
cat > metal3Cluster.yaml << EOF
apiVersion: infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1beta1
kind: Metal3Cluster
metadata:
  name: cluster-t1-m3cluster
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
spec:
  controlPlaneEndpoint:
    host: cluster-t1.example.com  # <cluster_name>.<base_domain>
    port: 6443
  noCloudProvider: true
EOF
oc apply -f metal3Cluster.yaml
```

Next we define the **OpenshiftAssistedControlPlane** resource. This provides:

* The pull-secret to pull down the containers from the registry  
* The default SSH Key for the core user  
* The version of Openshift to install  
* The **Metal3MachineTemplate** to use for the Controller Nodes  
* The number (replicas) of Controller Nodes to deploy

```shell
cat > openshiftAssistedControlPlane.yaml << EOF
apiVersion: controlplane.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1alpha2
kind: OpenshiftAssistedControlPlane
metadata:
  name: cluster-t1-oacp
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
  annotations: {}
    #cluster.x-k8s.io/release-image-repository-override: registry.ci.openshift.org/ocp/release
spec:
  openshiftAssistedConfigSpec:
    pullSecretRef:
      name: "pull-secret"     # Name of the secret we create next
    sshAuthorizedKey: "ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1yc…"  # SSH Key to login with
    nodeRegistration:
      kubeletExtraLabels:
        - 'metal3.io/uuid="${METADATA_UUID}"'
    nmStateConfigLabelSelector: 
      matchLabels:
        node: dellr6601        # This is the deployed NMState Config File
  distributionVersion: 4.19.10
  config:
    baseDomain: example.com
    pullSecretRef:
      name: "pull-secret"     # Name of the secret we create next
    sshAuthorizedKey: "ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1yc…"   # SSH Key to login with
  machineTemplate:
    infrastructureRef:
      apiVersion: infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1beta1
      kind: Metal3MachineTemplate
      name: cluster-t1-controller-template
      namespace: project-cluster-t1
  replicas: 1   # We are deploying a SNO cluster, so this is set to 1
EOF
oc apply -f openshiftAssistedControlPlane.yaml
```

At first look, it may seem like some things, such as the pull-secret and the SSH Key are redundant, however, you will notice that embedded within this configuration is an **OpenshiftAssistedConfigSpec**, which also requires these values.

The **nmStateConfigLabelSelector** points to the deployed [NMState Configuration that we created in the previous section](#configure-nmstateconfig-for-the-openshift-deployed-network-configuration).

Next we will create the **pull-secret** to pull the necessary containers. You can obtain your **pull-secret** from [here](https://console.redhat.com/openshift/install/pull-secret).

```shell
cat > pull-secret.yaml << EOF
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata: 
  name: pull-secret
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
data: 
  .dockerconfigjson: eyJhdXRocyI6eyJjbG... # The base64 encoded pull secret
type: kubernetes.io/dockerconfigjson
EOF
oc apply -f pull-secret.yaml
```

Finally we create the [**Metal3MachineTemplate**](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/metal3-io/cluster-api-provider-metal3/infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/Metal3MachineTemplate/v1beta1@v1.10.1) and [**Metal3DataTemplate**](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/metal3-io/cluster-api-provider-metal3/infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/Metal3DataTemplate/v1beta1@v1.10.1) . Since these are the last resources needed to define the deployment, once these are created the deployment will start. 

In this file you will:

* Set the hostSelector label to match the node you are deploying to  
* Set the checksum, checksumType, url and format for the image

The image you point to needs to have cloud-init built into it in order to access the config-drive that is used during the deployment.  Due to this, our example here is showing the Openstack image.

```shell
cat > metal3MachineTemplate.yaml << EOF
apiVersion: infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1beta1
kind: Metal3MachineTemplate
metadata:
  name: cluster-t1-controller
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
spec:
  nodeReuse: false
  template:
    spec:
      hostSelector:
        matchLabels:
          node: dellr6601   # Selecting which node to deploy SNO on
      automatedCleaningMode: metadata
      dataTemplate:
        name: cluster-t1-machine-template-controller
      image: 
        checksum: http://172.16.0.19/rhcos-4.19.10-x86_64-openstack.x86_64.qcow2.sha256
        checksumType: sha256
        url: http://172.16.0.19/rhcos-4.19.10-x86_64-openstack.x86_64.qcow2
        format: qcow2
---
apiVersion: infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1beta1
kind: Metal3DataTemplate
metadata:
   name: cluster-t1-machine-template-controller
   namespace: project-cluster-t1
spec:
   clusterName: cluster-t1
oc apply -f metal3MachineTemplate.yaml
```

An alternative to providing an image for deployment is to let the Hub Cluster use the RHCOS image that was used when it was deployed.  To do this, you would replace the **image**: section with a **customDeploy**: section as such:

```shell
...
    dataTemplate:
        name: cluster-t1-machine-template-controller
        customDeploy:                 # Replace the image: section with
          method: install_coreos      # these two lines
---
...
```

At this point jump down to the [Deployment Validation](#deployment-validation) section which will provide a number of commands to watch/troubleshoot the deployment.

## Deployment Type: Compact Cluster (3 controller/workers) {#deployment-type:-compact-cluster-(3-controller/workers)}

A Compact Cluster uses the same set of resources as a SNO cluster.  In this section we will call out the changes.

### Compact Cluster Deployment {#compact-cluster-deployment}

![][image6]

#### Resource Changes from a SNO Deployment {#resource-changes-from-a-sno-deployment}

The **OpenshiftAssistedControlPlane** resource has the following changes:

* The label selector for **nmStateConfigLabelSelector** changes to match all nodes to be used as controllers. We will use **role: controller**  
* The replicas changes from 1 to 3 for a 3 node cluster  
* Add the API and Ingress VIP IP addresses

```shell
cat > openshiftAssistedControlPlane.yaml << EOF
apiVersion: controlplane.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1alpha2
kind: OpenshiftAssistedControlPlane
metadata:
  name: cluster-t1-oacp
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
  annotations: {}
    #cluster.x-k8s.io/release-image-repository-override: registry.ci.openshift.org/ocp/release
spec:
  openshiftAssistedConfigSpec:
    pullSecretRef:
      name: "pull-secret"     # Name of the secret we create next
    sshAuthorizedKey: "ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1yc…"  # SSH Key to login with
    nodeRegistration:
      kubeletExtraLabels:
        - 'metal3.io/uuid="${METADATA_UUID}"'
    nmStateConfigLabelSelector: 
      matchLabels:
        role: controller       # This is the deployed NMState Config File
  distributionVersion: 4.19.10
  config:
   apiVIPs:
    - 172.17.0.201
    ingressVIPs:
    - 172.17.0.200
    baseDomain: example.com
    pullSecretRef:
      name: "pull-secret"     # Name of the secret we create next
    sshAuthorizedKey: "ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1yc…"   # SSH Key to login with
  machineTemplate:
    infrastructureRef:
      apiVersion: infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1beta1
      kind: Metal3MachineTemplate
      name: cluster-t1-controller-template
      namespace: project-cluster-t1
  replicas: 3   # We are deploying a Compact cluster, so this is set to 3
EOF
oc apply -f openshiftAssistedControlPlane.yaml
```

The **nmStateConfigLabelSelector** will actually match multiple NMStateConfig files, as it should. When it builds the deployment ISO, it will add all of the NMState Configs into the image and it will appropriately apply the corresponding NMState based on the MAC addresses it finds on the server.

The other file that needs to change is the [**Metal3MachineTemplate**](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/metal3-io/cluster-api-provider-metal3/infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/Metal3MachineTemplate/v1beta1@v1.10.1). We need to change the **hostSelector** to match all of the nodes that are part of the Compact Cluster, so we will use **role: controller**.

```shell
cat > metal3MachineTemplate.yaml << EOF
apiVersion: infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1beta1
kind: Metal3MachineTemplate
metadata:
  name: cluster-t1-controller
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
spec:
  nodeReuse: false
  template:
    spec:
      hostSelector:
        matchLabels:
          role: controller  # Selecting which nodes to deploy on
      automatedCleaningMode: metadata
      dataTemplate:
        name: cluster-t1-machine-template-controller
      image: 
        checksum: http://172.16.0.19/rhcos-4.19.10-x86_64-openstack.x86_64.qcow2.sha256
        checksumType: sha256
        url: http://172.16.0.19/rhcos-4.19.10-x86_64-openstack.x86_64.qcow2
        format: qcow2
#        customDeploy:
#          method: install_coreos
---
apiVersion: infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1beta1
kind: Metal3DataTemplate
metadata:
   name: cluster-t1-machine-template-controller
   namespace: project-cluster-t1
spec:
   clusterName: cluster-t1
oc apply -f metal3MachineTemplate.yaml
```

That is it.  Your cluster creation will start and you can jump down to the [Deployment Validation](#deployment-validation) section which will provide a number of commands to watch/troubleshoot the deployment.

## Deployment Type: Full Deployment (3 controllers \+ N workers) {#deployment-type:-full-deployment-(3-controllers-+-n-workers)}

The Full Deployment uses all of the same resource objects as the SNO and Compact Clusters, with some changes to them and adds 4 additional resource objects to the deployment:

* **OpenshiftAssistedConfigTemplate**  
* **MachineDeployment**  
* **Metal3MachineTemplate** (A second one for the Workers)  
* **Metal3DataTemplate** (A second one for the Workers)

Please note, if you create a Full Deployment with less than 6 nodes (3 controllers \+ 3 workers), your controllers will be deployed as Controller/Workers to support workload by default. 

### Full Deployment Resource Map {#full-deployment-resource-map}

![][image7]

#### Resource Changes from a SNO Deployment {#resource-changes-from-a-sno-deployment-1}

The full deployment has the same changes that the Compact Cluster would have for the SNO Configuration. As a recap, those changes are:

The **OpenshiftAssistedControlPlane** resource has the following changes from a SNO deployment:

* The label selector for **nmStateConfigLabelSelector** changes to match all nodes to be used as controllers. We will use **role: controller**  
* The replicas changes from 1 to 3 for a 3 controllers  
* Add the **API** and **Ingress** VIP IP addresses

    sshAuthorizedKey: "ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1yc…"  # SSH Key to login with
    nodeRegistration:
      kubeletExtraLabels:
        - 'metal3.io/uuid="${METADATA_UUID}"'
    nmStateConfigLabelSelector: 
      matchLabels:
        role: controller       # This is the deployed NMState Config File
  distributionVersion: 4.19.10
  config:
   apiVIPs:
    - 172.17.0.201

    sshAuthorizedKey: "ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1yc…"   # SSH Key to login with

      apiVersion: infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1beta1
      kind: Metal3MachineTemplate

The **nmStateConfigLabelSelector** will actually match multiple NMStateConfig files, as it should. When it builds the deployment ISO, it will add all of the NMState Configs into the image and it will appropriately apply the corresponding NMState based on the MAC addresses it finds on the server.

The other file that needs to change is the [**Metal3MachineTemplate**](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/metal3-io/cluster-api-provider-metal3/infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/Metal3MachineTemplate/v1beta1@v1.10.1). #### New Resources {#new-resources}

The [MachineDeployment](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api/cluster.x-k8s.io/MachineDeployment/v1beta1@v1.0.0) is used to define the number of Worker Nodes to be deployed in the cluster, and tie together the OpenshiftAssistedConfigTemplate (below) to the [Metal3MachineTemplate](https://doc.crds.dev/github.com/metal3-io/cluster-api-provider-metal3/infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/Metal3MachineTemplate/v1beta1@v1.10.1) (above)

```shell
cat > metal3MachineDeployment.yaml << EOF
apiVersion: cluster.x-k8s.io/v1beta1
kind: MachineDeployment
metadata:
  name: cluster-t1-worker-machine-deployment
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
  labels:
    cluster.x-k8s.io/cluster-name: cluster-t1
spec:
  clusterName: cluster-t1
  replicas: 3   # Set this to how many Worker Nodes you are wanting to deploy
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      cluster.x-k8s.io/cluster-name: cluster-t1
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        cluster.x-k8s.io/cluster-name: cluster-t1
    spec:
      clusterName: cluster-t1
      bootstrap: 
        configRef:
          name: cluster-t1-worker-oact
          apiVersion: bootstrap.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1alpha1
          kind: OpenshiftAssistedConfigTemplate
      infrastructureRef:
        name: cluster-t1-workers
        apiVersion: infrastructure.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1alpha3
        kind: Metal3MachineTemplate
EOF
oc apply -f metal3MachineDeployment.yaml
```

Next we have to create an **OpenshiftAsssitedConfigTemplate** that defines the worker nodes in the cluster.

```shell
cat > openshiftAssistedConfigTemplate.yaml << EOF
apiVersion: bootstrap.cluster.x-k8s.io/v1alpha1
kind: OpenshiftAssistedConfigTemplate
metadata:
  name: cluster-t1-worker-oact
  namespace: project-cluster-t1
  labels:
    cluster.x-k8s.io/cluster-name: cluster-t1
spec:
  template:
    spec:
      nodeRegistration:
        # name: '${METADATA_NAME}'
        kubeletExtraLabels:
          - 'metal3.io/uuid="${METADATA_UUID}"'
      pullSecretRef:
        name: "pull-secret"
      nmStateConfigLabelSelector:
        matchLabels:
          role: worker
      sshAuthorizedKey: "ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1yc…"   # SSH Key to login with
EOF
oc apply -f openshiftAssistedConfigTemplate.yaml
```

That is it.  Your cluster creation will start and  you can continue with the [Deployment Validation](#deployment-validation) section below which will provide a number of commands to watch/troubleshoot the deployment.

# Deployment Validation {#deployment-validation}

After you have submitted all of the YAML for your deployment, here is what you should look for in the order they will appear. These commands assume your current active project is your cluster project.

| Commands | Description |
| :---- | :---- |
| **Part 1 of Deployment: Baremetal Provisioning** |  |
| oc get secret | In this output you will first see a secret called **\*merged-pull-secret** followed shortly after by the creation of a secret for each baremetal node you’re deploying. Each of these is the ignition file for that node. You can look at it with: oc get secret \<secret\_name\> | grep value \\ awk ‘{print $2}’| base64 \-d |
| oc get bmh | After the ignition secret is created, the baremetal host will go to **Provisioning** State when Metal3 boots the node. The host will boot, Metal3 will write RHCOS to the disk and then reboot the node.  Once this reboot is triggered (before the node actually boots), the BMH state will go to **Provisioned**.  Metal3 considers its job done at this point. |
| oc logs \-n multicluster-engine \\ $(oc get pods \-n multicluster-engine \\ | grep capm3 | awk '{print $1}')  | If you have issues with nodes being provisioned, you can check the console of the node. If the node has an IP address, you can ssh to it as the core using using the SSH Key you provided in the BMH Secret.  Additionally, you can look at the Metal3 logs using this command. |
| oc get aci \<aci\_name\> \-o yaml | This will output the status of a number of deployment checks and can provide useful information as to why the deployment may not be progressing. |
| **Part 2 of Deployment: Openshift Installation** |  |
| oc get aci \<aci\_name\> \-o yaml \\ | grep \-A1 ‘ progress:’ | In addition to providing validation steps, this can also be used to monitor the progress of the Openshift Installation. This command will grab the percentage completion of the Openshift Deployment. |
| clusterctl describe cluster \--namespace \\ \<project\_name\> \<cluster\_name\> \\ \--show-conditions=all | This is a useful command that queries the Cluster API and shows the overall deployment process.  You can actually run this after the deployment starts and it will also tell you where Metal3 is in the deployment. |

If you do not already have the clusterctl command, you can obtain it following the instructions [here](https://cluster-api.sigs.k8s.io/user/quick-start#install-clusterctl).

Once the deployment is complete, the kubeadmin password and the kubeconfig are created as secrets in your namespace. Additionally, you can get the kubeconfig file for the deployment with this command:

clusterctl get kubeconfig \-n project-cluster-t1 cluster-t1 \> multinode-kubeconfig
